test('order status updates correctly', function () {
    $order = Order::factory()->create(['status' => 'pending']);

    $order->updateStatus('completed');

    $this->assertEquals('completed', $order->fresh()->status, 'Status should update to completed');
    $this->assertNotNull($order->completed_at, 'Completed timestamp should be set');
    $this->assertTrue($order->notifications()->exists(), 'Notification should be sent');
});

This example verifies not just that the method runs without errors but also that all side effects (status update, timestamp, notification) occur as expected. Traditional assertions like `assert(true)` would pass even if nothing happened, whereas this approach catches real bugs.
